  "text": "The HTTP filter factory registration and instantiation process in Envoy v1.31.2 follows a multi-stage pipeline:\n\n## Filter Factory Registration\n\nHTTP filters are registered by implementing the **NamedHttpFilterConfigFactory** interface defined in `envoy/server/filter_config.h`. This interface derives from **HttpFilterConfigFactoryBase** and requires implementation of `createFilterFactoryFromProto()` method, which takes a protobuf config message and returns an `Http::FilterFactoryCb` - a callback function that instantiates filters per-request.\n\nFilters are typically registered using the `REGISTER_FACTORY` macro, which registers the factory with the global **Registry::FactoryRegistry<NamedHttpFilterConfigFactory>**.\n\n## Configuration Processing\n\nWhen the HTTP connection manager is configured, the **FilterChainHelper** class in `source/common/http/filter_chain_helper.h` processes HTTP filter configurations. The `processFilter()` method:\n\n1. Retrieves the factory from the registry using `Config::Utility::getAndCheckFactory<NeutralNamedHttpFilterFactory>()`\n2. Calls `factory->createFilterFactoryFromProto()` to obtain a `FilterFactoryCb` callback\n3. Wraps the callback in a **FilterConfigProviderPtr** and stores it in a **FilterFactoriesList**\n\nFor dynamic filters, the **HttpDynamicFilterConfigProviderImpl** in `source/common/filter/config_discovery_impl.h` handles runtime filter instantiation via `instantiateFilterFactory()`, which also calls the factory's `createFilterFactoryFromProto()` method.\n\n## Filter Chain Creation for Factories\n\nThe **FilterChainUtility::createFilterChainForFactories()** function in `source/common/http/filter_chain_helper.cc` iterates through stored filter factories and calls `manager.applyFilterFactoryCb()` for each one, passing the factory's callback.\n\n## Per-Request Filter Instantiation\n\nWhen a new HTTP stream is created, the **FilterManager** in `source/common/http/filter_manager.h` calls `applyFilterFactoryCb()` (implemented in `source/common/http/filter_manager.cc` at line 551):\n\n```cpp\nvoid FilterManager::applyFilterFactoryCb(FilterContext context, FilterFactoryCb& factory) {\n  FilterChainFactoryCallbacksImpl callbacks(*this, context);\n  factory(callbacks);\n}\n```\n\nThis invokes the stored callback with a **FilterChainFactoryCallbacksImpl** object, which implements **Http::FilterChainFactoryCallbacks**. The actual filter instances are created when the callback calls methods like:\n\n- `addStreamDecoderFilter()` - adds decoder-only filters\n- `addStreamEncoderFilter()` - adds encoder-only filters  \n- `addStreamFilter()` - adds dual encoder/decoder filters\n\nThese methods (lines 918-938 in filter_manager.h) wrap the filter instances in **ActiveStreamDecoderFilter** and **ActiveStreamEncoderFilter** objects, which manage the filter's lifecycle, iteration state, and data processing on the request/response paths.\n\n## Key Components\n\n- **NamedHttpFilterConfigFactory**: Interface for filter factories, registered in the global registry\n- **FilterChainHelper**: Processes static filter configs during HCM initialization\n- **HttpDynamicFilterConfigProviderImpl**: Provides runtime filter instantiation via xDS\n- **FilterManager**: Manages per-stream filter chains and execution\n- **FilterChainFactoryCallbacksImpl**: Bridge between factory callbacks and actual filter creation\n- **ActiveStreamDecoderFilter/EncoderFilter**: Wrappers for filter instances that handle iteration and state management"
}

